DSS.title: Create CSVs of All Studies and Datafiles

comments.body:
Produced this with this code. Maybe this could be a rake task sometime

```
def no_lines(field)
    unless field.nil?
        return field.gsub("\n", " ")
    end
end


require 'csv' 
study_file = "#{Rails.root}/log/study_data.csv"
studies = Study.all
headers = ["id", "legacy_id", "studynum", "title", "medium", "icpsr_num", "url", "directory", "folder", "r_flag", "timestamp", "auto_refresh", "note", "roper", "voyager_id", "resource_id"]

# note field needs scrubbing, lines removed. 
CSV.open(study_file, 'w', write_headers: true, headers: headers) do |writer|
  studies.each do |study| 
  writer << [study.id, study.legacy_id, study.studynum, study.title, study.medium, study.icpsr_num, study.url, study.directory, study.folder, study.r_flag, study.timestamp, study.auto_refresh, no_lines(study.note), study.roper, study.voyager_id, study.resource_id] 
  end
end

data_file = "#{Rails.root}/log/data_file_data.csv"
data_files = DataFile.all
data_headers = ["id", "legacy_id", "files", "size", "comp_size", "line_count", "line_length", "part", "file_type_a", "file_type_b", "flag_one", "flag_two", "file_type_tech", "note", "study_num", "permission", "time_stamp", "original_study_id", "study_id"]

CSV.open(data_file, 'w', write_headers: true, headers: data_headers) do |writer|
    data_files.each do |data_file|
        writer << [data_file.id, data_file.legacy_id, data_file.files, data_file.size, data_file.comp_size, data_file.line_count, data_file.line_length, data_file.part, data_file.file_type_a, data_file.file_type_b, data_file.flag_one, data_file.flag_two, data_file.file_type_tech, data_file.note, data_file.study_num, data_file.permission, data_file.timestamp, data_file.original_study_id, data_file.study_id]
    end
end
```
sent to bobray. leaving open until he confirms he doesn't need any changes.

cicognara-static.title: Can we use something like CollectionBuilder uses to implement a search bar?

comments.body:
I'm encountering this in other projects: stakeholders don't want to lose fielded searching and filtering.

This is a larger challenge: how to simulate a relational database in a static site without a relational database back end?

See comment from lunr developer: https://github.com/olivernn/lunr.js/issues/373.  I also note that the Lunr codebase hasn't been touched in over 3 years and the issues have piled up. so I don't think it is active any longer.

The most actively-maintained Javascript indexer I've found so far is Fuse.js: https://github.com/krisk/fuse.  Note, however, that the author warns about the limits of in-memory indexes getting too large: https://github.com/krisk/Fuse/discussions/577

figgy.title: Use Selenium Standalone instead of Webdrivers
Add Derivative Health to Health Report
Repeatably Generate a Report on the Cloud Preservation Status of All Resources

comments.body:
We ran this on production and found most resources failed because metadata checksums didn't match.

This is a flaw in checking metadata checksums as an idea. We add fields to FileSet over time, so the serialization changes. For instance, we've added `service_targets`. So if a FileSet is ingested on October 1, it says the following on both the cloud service and locally:

```
{
"title" => ["Test"]
}
```

but if we then add `service_targets` on October 3, locally it now says:

```
{
"title" => ["Test"],
"service_targets" => []
}
```
. The file's still preserved - if we restore the old file into the new it works, we're backwards compatible. However there's no way to translate the checksum for the old file serialization to the new.

We might want to change preservation metadata validation by storing the lock token on the object's metadata in GCS and checking that. We'd have to change our preservation function too.

Another idea is to not include properties that don't have values in the metadata json. This seems a bit simpler.

Either option will require re-preserving all the metadata targets.

comments.body: As identified by @carolyncole, coveralls has been removed from PDC Describe.

Looks like this is the gem that lets us authenticate to orcid and get a token: https://github.com/datacite/omniauth-orcid

We need to register our application (there is a staging and a production environment). For full access we need to be organization orcid members, and I've asked on slack for confirmation that this is so.

We need to provide a contact email address and a secondary email address, as well as the URLs the application will use and the redirect urls that omniauth will use. Form is here, for reference: https://info.orcid.org/register-a-client-application-production-member-api/

The page also says we should expect some lead time:

    Note: This process is not fully automated. There may be a delay before we respond to you with credentials or a demo request after you complete this form.

There appears to be pretty good documentation for how to configure this in rails:
https://github.com/datacite/omniauth-orcid#rails

researchdata.title: Responsive Footer is resized oddly after upgrade to Drupal 10

comments.body:
Possible fix idea. This isn't something coming from our theming SCSS or JS. It's internal to Drupal's image style modules. 

- [x] Try to explicitly rebuild any cached image styles 
- [x] Check the media queries the responsive image module is using to see if something needs to be adjusted.
- [x] Stop using responsive image styles for the footer.

The problem seems related to when the media query for larges screens > 1275 is applied using Drupal's responsive image styles feature. When I remove that option the images display reasonably on all size screens. 

Before [Private Zenhub Image](https://api.zenhub.com/attachedFiles/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBMWtoQVE9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--d378ba94399ac198ac33bd1944517d51467a3d82/Screenshot%202023-10-10%20at%203.04.11%20PM.png)

After

[Private Zenhub Image](https://api.zenhub.com/attachedFiles/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBMW9oQVE9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--01043f5d3a7b58b9e3c35fbe46f0af2c7370afb7/Screenshot%202023-10-10%20at%203.04.17%20PM.png)
See staging environment. Given the nature of this site (we plan to move it to WDS hosting in the next 6-9 months I think this is a good enough fix to remove the block to migrate to Drupal 10.
